      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation software (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) must be verified under a documented SQA plan including version control, regression testing, and audit trail.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is used under a validated installation with documented SQA procedures. Regression test suite executed at installation; version-controlled input decks stored in institutional repository. SQA documentation reviewed and found compliant with FDA guidance on software validation. Achieved level exceeds required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from NAFEMS and ASME V&V 10 must be reproduced within published tolerances to confirm correct solver implementation.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical solver verified against NAFEMS LE1, LE3, and LE10 benchmark problems; all results within 1% of reference solutions. Contact mechanics verified using Hertzian contact benchmark. Code verification evidence documented in solver qualification report rev. 2.1."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change less than 5% between successive refinements; Richardson extrapolation GCI reported.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed (coarse: 0.8 mm global, medium: 0.5 mm, fine: 0.3 mm at screw-rod interface). Stiffness QoI changed 3.1% between medium and fine meshes; yield force changed 2.4%. GCI for fine mesh: 1.8%. Medium mesh adopted for production runs as accuracy-cost optimum. Discretization error within acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must converge to below 1e-6 for all load steps; force-displacement equilibrium verified at each increment.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson nonlinear solver used with displacement increments of 0.1 mm. Force and displacement residuals converge to 1e-7 at each load step. Equilibrium checks performed at 10%, 50%, and 100% of applied load. No divergence events observed across all 11 model instances. Solver error assessed as negligible."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup by a second analyst; documented simulation protocol followed for all model instances.",
      "rationale": "Simulation protocol document rev. 1.4 specifies all boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and load application procedures. All 11 model instances set up by primary analyst and independently reviewed by second analyst with 8 years FEA experience. Discrepancies resolved before results extraction. Use error risk assessed as low."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum mechanics assumptions (linear elastic titanium alloy, rigid UHMWPE blocks, frictional contact) must be justified relative to observed experimental failure modes.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V screw and rod modeled as linear elastic (E=114 GPa, nu=0.34) consistent with pre-yield loading regime targeted by F1717. UHMWPE vertebral body simulants modeled as rigid per ASTM F1717 protocol. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at screw-rod interface calibrated to torque-to-yield data. Large-displacement formulation (NLGEOM ON) captures geometric nonlinearity at 40 mm displacement. Model form appropriate for the COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of test specimens; traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties (E, yield strength, UTS) obtained from lot-specific certified material test reports for each of the 11 test constructs. Screw and rod geometry inputs from CMM measurements (±0.005 mm accuracy). Torque application confirmed from calibrated torque wrench records. A screening sensitivity study ranked cortical bone modulus and screw-rod friction as dominant QoI drivers; these inputs received highest measurement fidelity. Input traceability matrix completed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥5 experimental constructs from production lots; lot traceability and dimensional inspection documented.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-lot components with full lot traceability. Dimensional inspection of all screws and rods performed prior to testing (CMM, ±0.005 mm). Constructs assembled per F1717 protocol by trained technicians at two independent laboratories (FDA OSEL and DePuy Synthes test facility). Sample representativeness confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span at least two loading rates and two laboratory environments to assess condition sensitivity.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted under a single quasi-static loading rate (5 mm/min) as specified by ASTM F1717. Only one test condition was evaluated; rate sensitivity and environmental variation were not explored experimentally. This factor is below the required level. The gap is acknowledged; the screening sensitivity study suggests loading rate has low influence on stiffness QoI but this was not formally validated. Risk accepted given medium model influence and medium decision consequence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs must be traceable to experimentally measured values; correspondence between simulation and test inputs documented for each construct.",
      "rationale": "One-to-one correspondence established between each of the 11 FEA model instances and the corresponding physical test construct. CMM geometry, lot-specific material properties, and recorded assembly torques used as direct FEA inputs. Input equivalency matrix reviewed by independent analyst. No systematic offsets identified between simulation and test input parameters."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; individual construct comparisons and aggregate statistics reported.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs compared: construct stiffness (E/uval=0.87), yield force (E/uval=1.43), and force at 40 mm (E/uval=1.61). All three E/uval values below the pre-established threshold of 1.96. Individual construct comparisons show no systematic bias. Bland-Altman plots confirm agreement across the measurement range. Output comparison exceeds required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) must be directly linked to the regulatory submission claim and to clinically relevant failure modes.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs are the primary metrics required by FDA guidance for pedicle screw construct evaluation under F1717. Construct stiffness relates to load-sharing with the spine; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement relate to fatigue and fracture risk. QoI relevance confirmed by regulatory affairs review and documented in the V&V plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be conducted under conditions sufficiently similar to the COU that extrapolation risk is low; similarity argument documented.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the exact device configuration (7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screw, 5.5 mm rod, UHMWPE simulants) under the same F1717 protocol as the intended regulatory submission. No extrapolation in geometry, material, or loading regime required. Validation activity relevance rated as high; similarity argument documented in the V&V plan section 4.3."
    }
  ],
